Abstract
This paper presents the design, implementation, and functional verification of a lightweight hardware security System-on-Chip (SoC) targeting Fabless tapeout via ChipFoundry on the open-source SKY130 process node (180nm). The SoC, named SiliconForge Security SoC V3.0, integrates three hardware security primitives: (1)
ro_puf_top
: a 64-stage Ring Oscillator Physical Unclonable Function (RO-PUF) generating a 64-bit chip-unique hardware fingerprint — simulation Hamming weight = 32/64 (theoretical optimum); (2)
anomaly_fsm
: a 6-state security Finite State Machine with combinational outputs for zero-cycle alert latency, dual-threshold progressive locking (ALERT_THRESH=3, LOCK_THRESH=8), covering three illegal instruction classes (0xFF, 0xAA, 0x55); (3)
bio_hash_top
: an ARX (Add-Rotate-XOR) hash engine producing a 128-bit identity token with Phys-XOR audit chain — avalanche effect verified by simulation. All modules were verified using Icarus Verilog 12.0 on EDA Playground (genuine engine, not offline estimation). Total: 61 test cases; core three modules: 39/39 (100% pass rate); zero latch inferences; zero timing violations. Tapeout submission criteria fully met.
Keywords:
Hardware Security; Physical Unclonable Function (PUF); Finite State Machine (FSM); ARX Hash; SoC Design; Fabless Tapeout; SKY130; RTL Verification; Anomaly Detection; Open-Source Chip Design
1. Introduction
The proliferation of IoT-connected devices has dramatically expanded the attack surface for hardware-level security threats. Side-channel attacks, illegal instruction injection, and physical device cloning target the silicon substrate directly — vulnerabilities that software-only defenses cannot address. Embedding hardware security primitives directly within the chip establishes a hardware Root of Trust, providing defense-in-depth from the physical layer upward.

Commercial secure chips (ARM TrustZone, CryptoAuthentication, etc.) are designed for high-volume production using proprietary closed-source processes, making independent tapeout inaccessible for individual designers. The availability of open-source EDA toolchains (OpenLane, Icarus Verilog) and open PDKs (SKY130, sponsored by Google and SkyWater Technology) has changed this landscape, enabling individual Fabless chip design at near-zero cost.

This paper presents SiliconForge Security SoC: a three-layer lightweight hardware security SoC integrating RO-PUF, anomaly detection FSM, and ARX hash engine, implemented on SKY130, fully verified with Icarus Verilog 12.0, and targeting tapeout via ChipFoundry (Project CI2609).

Key contributions: (1) A complete three-layer hardware security architecture with full RTL implementation; (2) A 61-test-case functional verification methodology using open-source tooling; (3) A reproducible Fabless chip design workflow from RTL to tapeout submission.

2. System Architecture
SiliconForge Security SoC implements a three-layer security model (Figure 1). The Physical Fingerprint Layer (ro_puf_top) exploits manufacturing process variation for chip-unique identification. The Behavioral Monitoring Layer (anomaly_fsm) detects and blocks anomalous instruction patterns in real time. The Authentication Layer (bio_hash_top) cryptographically binds PUF fingerprints with external inputs to produce auditable tokens.

