3. Core Module Design
3.1 RO-PUF Physical Fingerprint Module (ro_puf_top)
Ring Oscillator PUFs exploit uncontrollable manufacturing process variation in transistor threshold voltage, gate oxide thickness, and interconnect width. 64 pairs of ring oscillators produce frequency differences resolved by comparators into a 64-bit unique fingerprint. The theoretical Hamming distance between any two instances approaches 50%, ensuring maximal inter-device uniqueness and minimal predictability.

PUF_response[i] = (freq_RO_A[i] > freq_RO_B[i]) ? 1 : 0,   i ∈ [0, 63]
Control logic implements a 3-state FSM (IDLE → SAMPLE → DONE) with a 32-cycle stabilization window. A valid signal flags sampling completion. Simulation result: Hamming weight = 32/64 — the theoretical optimum, confirming maximum entropy and uniformly distributed fingerprint bits.

3.2 Anomaly Detection FSM (anomaly_fsm)
The FSM implements dual-threshold progressive security escalation across six states. V3.0 adopts combinational assign-based outputs, eliminating one clock cycle of register latency and achieving zero-cycle alert response.

IDLE ──cmd_valid──► MONITOR MONITOR ──illegal_cmd──► DETECT (anomaly_cnt++) DETECT ──cnt ≥ 3──► ALERT_S (soft alert asserted) DETECT ──cnt ≥ 8──► LOCK_S (permanent hardware lock) ALERT_S ──continued illegal──► DETECT LOCK_S ──(permanent)──► only rst_n releases RESET_S ──────────────► IDLE Figure 2: anomaly_fsm State Transition Diagram
Illegal instruction types: 0xFF (all-ones / invalid opcode), 0xAA (privilege escalation), 0x55 (overflow trigger). Dual-threshold: ALERT_THRESH=3 (soft warning), LOCK_THRESH=8 (hard lock). Once in LOCK_S, no software instruction can release the lock — only hardware rst_n (active-low reset) restores normal operation, preventing any software-based attack recovery.

3.3 ARX Hash Engine (bio_hash_top)
ARX (Add-Rotate-XOR) structures are the foundation of modern lightweight cryptography (Salsa20, ChaCha20, BLAKE2) because they require no S-box lookup tables and rely solely on integer addition, rotation, and XOR — mapping efficiently to hardware with minimal area.

bio_hash_top applies 8 ARX rounds to a 128-bit state (four 32-bit registers s0–s3), initialized with PUF fingerprint and external biometric data XORed against four round constants (RC0–RC3, derived from the golden ratio). The 128-bit identity token is extracted post-finalization. A 64-bit Phys-XOR audit value is output, linking the token to the originating PUF fingerprint for external integrity verification.

Round: s0 += s1 + RC;   s1 = ROTL(s1, 13) XOR (s0 + s1 + RC)
Simulation confirmed: avalanche effect (1-bit input change → completely different 128-bit token); determinism (identical inputs → identical outputs); Phys-XOR linkage to PUF data.

